comments.body:
This was also just reported as affecting the following Item:

https://dataspace.princeton.edu/handle/88435/dsp017p88ck26d?mode=full
Authorization *is* properly functioning for authenticated users with administrative access.

The Policies for the Bundle and Bitstream are also set properly:

![image.png](https://images.zenhubusercontent.com/5b5b6aed981c3204c9ed06c8/831c2815-c13f-43e1-96cc-089aa635389f)

Perhaps this is an error with the JSPUI theme?

I am still struggling to find where the authorization bug lies for these cases. The following is an example of an Item which has identical policies, but *is* accessible from the WWW by anonymous users:

https://dataspace.princeton.edu/handle/88435/dsp016w924f699?mode=full

The error seems to be related to the absence of dissertations containing metadata values for `pu.embargo.lift` and `pu.embargo.terms`. Both *must* be present (however, I unfortunately could not locate in the code base where this functionality lies).

At the Policy level, there are improperly parsed embargo dates, leading to a failure to lift embargoes when necessary:

![image.png](https://images.zenhubusercontent.com/5b5b6aed981c3204c9ed06c8/bd3cf9ea-5841-4102-810c-368ee5a007dd)

I shall see about addressing these cases (they seem to affect the batches published on 2021-10-04)

comments.body: @regineheberlein in this issue https://github.com/pulibrary/bibdata/issues/1963 we also added rare$xmr, which doesn't have a prefix sca. Is the location rare$xmr still part of this SC location group with reading room use only?

Yes, you're right. "xmr" is part of the request. I wasn't thinking of the ReCAP ones because their user-facing code still starts with "sca" (i.e., the archivists use "scarcpxmr" but it maps to "xmr" behind the scenes). I guess we're back to hardcoding then. :-(
@regineheberlein thanks! Your suggestion can always be used + any other location which is part of this group and doesn't start with sca.
